{"pageProps":{"post":{"_createdAt":"2022-06-21T08:09:15Z","_id":"315dc882-dfe1-4d29-8a04-488b9b2a797a","author":{"image":{"_type":"image","asset":{"_ref":"image-339f8e320ddfad52225d31a181b162996e1c02d1-876x876-png","_type":"reference"}},"name":"üëæ Game Master"},"body":[{"_key":"6ca9246790f3","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"958846ba26720","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"What is Beta?"}],"markDefs":[],"style":"h2"},{"_key":"cd8863353b8e","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"d04d9e4adccb0","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"In finance, beta measures the volatility of a stock, which is the risk of a given company relative to the market. According to the risk-return model, higher beta stands for higher risk and higher return, whereas lower beta suggests a lower risk and lower return."}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"4916e3448d3e","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"de2c262852ad0","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Depending on the context, beta is also referred to as the "},{"_key":"de2c262852ad1","_type":"span","marks":["em"],"text":"systematic risk"},{"_key":"de2c262852ad2","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":" or "},{"_key":"de2c262852ad3","_type":"span","marks":["em"],"text":"hedge ratio"},{"_key":"de2c262852ad4","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"."}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"9af1c3a46452","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"c9a6638de4a10","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Application of Beta"}],"markDefs":[],"style":"h2"},{"_key":"6752c23bdec9","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"39492f7b3c310","_type":"span","marks":["strong"],"text":"The market has a beta of 1.0."},{"_key":"39492f7b3c311","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":" Stocks with a beta greater than 1.0 suggest higher volatility (understand volatility as fluctuation in prices) with respect to the broader market. Stocks with a beta less than 1.0 suggest lower volatility with respect to the market."}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"cadb24ab2f8b","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"acd535d0ce460","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Different to "},{"_key":"acd535d0ce461","_type":"span","marks":["67873341a3e0"],"text":"Alpha (Œ±)"},{"_key":"acd535d0ce462","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":", beta had no ‚Äúabsolute definition,‚Äù which means neither a high beta nor a low beta is ‚Äúabsolutely‚Äù better. For investors seeking stable and slow returns, a low beta might be preferred. On the other hand, a high beta stock could be selected if an investor is looking for a ‚Äúhigh-risk high return‚Äù investment."}],"markDefs":[{"_key":"67873341a3e0","_type":"link","href":"https://www.notion.so/Alpha-b609ed9eae2e42b0a548538de422818f"}],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"02b63a079344","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"ada41f3d3ca60","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Calculation"}],"markDefs":[],"style":"h2"},{"_key":"a1b86019e113","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"a6a44f14d3130","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"There are two ways to derive beta, depending on how much you want to know, and where you want to apply this tool. I will mention the straightforward method first and the more concise method next."}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"294e66c4b006","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"06a6df186d910","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Method 1: Formula"}],"markDefs":[],"style":"h4"},{"_key":"d8f2675698f2","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"8efed0eb4d270","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"As mentioned, beta is a measurement of volatility. In statistics, two common approaches to measuring volatility are Variance (Link here "},{"_key":"8efed0eb4d271","_type":"span","marks":["e3103c953f3b"],"text":"Mean, Variance and Covariance"},{"_key":"8efed0eb4d272","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":") (which calculates the fluctuation of a data group itself) and covariance (Link here "},{"_key":"8efed0eb4d273","_type":"span","marks":["2ede299dfaae"],"text":"Mean, Variance and Covariance"},{"_key":"8efed0eb4d274","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":") (which measures the volatility of a data group with respect to another one). Numerically, beta takes these two approaches in its calculation and suggests the fluctuation of a stock‚Äôs price compared with the benchmark:"}],"markDefs":[{"_key":"e3103c953f3b","_type":"link","href":"https://www.notion.so/Mean-Variance-and-Covariance-06b2968a95ba4fb587bb801cd56f3fee"},{"_key":"2ede299dfaae","_type":"link","href":"https://www.notion.so/Mean-Variance-and-Covariance-06b2968a95ba4fb587bb801cd56f3fee"}],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"8b25e6d6c5e3","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"8ef16be75a470","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":""}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"6c96abf36ec6","_type":"image","asset":{"_ref":"image-6fe3c81e8fdd5e9d16a2eb43cd9fdcab4899e333-1628x198-png","_type":"reference"}},{"_key":"8d9765474012","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"b2d1885260720","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Method 2: Regression"}],"markDefs":[],"style":"h4"},{"_key":"721af72000da","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"260806db31a30","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Technically speaking, both Beta and "},{"_key":"260806db31a31","_type":"span","marks":["60f7803dd908"],"text":"Alpha (Œ±)"},{"_key":"260806db31a32","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":" are derived through regression analysis."}],"markDefs":[{"_key":"60f7803dd908","_type":"link","href":"https://www.notion.so/Alpha-b609ed9eae2e42b0a548538de422818f"}],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"f0e75ea86d3c","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"4df1309934021","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":""}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"cf6b9a58c958","_type":"image","asset":{"_ref":"image-5b82e00d4eb74154beef15824591709567277fa6-1586x406-png","_type":"reference"}},{"_key":"209f19e3d4f4","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"ac7b2f50df4c0","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"To derive Beta, we need to general a regression model that finds the relation of stock A‚Äôs price relative to the benchmark. "},{"_key":"ac7b2f50df4c1","_type":"span","marks":["strong"],"text":"The slope of the result will be the beta, and the intercept of the result will be the "},{"_key":"ac7b2f50df4c2","_type":"span","marks":["strong","49a273fcbd62"],"text":"Alpha (Œ±)"},{"_key":"ac7b2f50df4c3","_type":"span","marks":["strong"],"text":" (the excess return a stock generates with respect to the benchmark)."}],"markDefs":[{"_key":"49a273fcbd62","_type":"link","href":"https://www.notion.so/Alpha-b609ed9eae2e42b0a548538de422818f"}],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"bb629e81d971","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"637e4742abc8","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":""}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"09f99ecc1ccf","_type":"image","asset":{"_ref":"image-7c71ed8d0444cfd542c5c9c6b40f3aa211ec3545-2186x972-png","_type":"reference"}},{"_key":"c4112593d55b","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"66eab683b4060","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":""}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"295ffa22e9e5","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"9e513e76e7bb0","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Application of Beta - the CAPM Model"}],"markDefs":[],"style":"h2"},{"_key":"54767aec4215","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"b45e541fe2750","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Beta is an important component in the "},{"_key":"b45e541fe2751","_type":"span","marks":["1018ccc10f07"],"text":"The Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM)"},{"_key":"b45e541fe2752","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":", which models the expected return of a stock. Since beta measures the volatility of a stock relative to the market, by multiplying beta by the market‚Äôs expected return and adding back the risk-free rate, an investor could calculate the theoretical rate of return of the selected stock."}],"markDefs":[{"_key":"1018ccc10f07","_type":"link","href":"https://www.notion.so/The-Capital-Asset-Pricing-Model-CAPM-3d79313bd8d3476d983e4f967e142c74"}],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"851b25cef679","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"a4b5baedac700","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":""}],"markDefs